<TR>
<TD>&nbsp;<FONT FACE="Verdana,
Arial, Helvetica"
SIZE="2" color="red"><B>

Buffer Overflows a Serious Threat

</B></FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE WIDTH="389" BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=6>
<TR>
<TD>
<FONT FACE="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="2">
<p> 
<FONT COLOR="gray" size=-2><B>contributed by Scr1pt</B>
</FONT>
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="BLACK">

A recently released report by the Hurwitz Group labels buffer overflow
attacks as a significant threat to web security. These 'news' articles
then go on and on about how great SECURED by Memco is.  This new
software incorporates the patented technology of Stack Overflow
Protection (STOP) which claims to relocate system stack memory to
random areas.  So now instead of forcing vendors to write better code
you can pay more money to fix a problem that shouldn't be there in the
first place. 

<p>
<a href="http://www.hurwitz.com/">Hurwitz Group</a><br>
<a href="http://www.memco.com/">Memco</a>- Buffer Overflow Report<br>
<a href="http://www.l0pht.com/advisories/bufero.html">How to write
Buffer Overflows</a><br>
<a href="http://nt.excite.com/news/bw/990203/ca-memco-software">
Excite News</a><br>
<a href="http://www.internetwk.com/news0299/news020399-5.htm">Internet
Week</a><br>
<p>
</FONT> 
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>
<!-- End Day -->
<!-- Begin Day --> 
<TABLE BGCOLOR="#555555" WIDTH="401" BORDER=0
CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=3>
<TR>
<TD>

<TABLE BGCOLOR="#303030" WIDTH="395" 
BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=2>
<TR>
<TD>&nbsp;<FONT FACE="Verdana,
Arial, Helvetica"
SIZE="2" color="red"><B>

FAO Leaked Personal Info.

</B></FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE WIDTH="389" BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=6>
<TR>
<TD>
<FONT FACE="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="2">
<p> 
<FONT COLOR="gray" size=-2><B>contributed by cipher</B>
</FONT>
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="BLACK">

Yesterday HNN broke the story about FAO Schwarz leaking the personal
information of its customers  onto the web.  After completing an
online form FAO offered its customers two options, pay online or print
out the form and mail or fax it in.  It was this second 'Offline'
option that had problems.  By changing the 'userid' field in the URL
you could view any ones personal information who had purchased items
at FAO and chose the 'Offline' option. Name, address, email, and phone
number information was available.<br>
FAO failed to respond to several emails from HNN. The misconfigured
script continued to be accessible for most of the day yesterday but
was finnally fixed after Wired ran their version of story.

<p>
<a href="/archive.html?020399.htm">Yesterdays News on HNN</a><br>
<a
href="http://www.wired.com/news/news/technology/story/17716.html">Wired</a><br>
<p>
</FONT> 
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>
<!-- End Day -->
<!-- Begin Day --> 
<TABLE BGCOLOR="#555555" WIDTH="401" BORDER=0
CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=3>
<TR>
<TD>

<TABLE BGCOLOR="#303030" WIDTH="395" 
BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=2>
<TR>
<TD>&nbsp;<FONT FACE="Verdana,
Arial, Helvetica"
SIZE="2" color="red"><B>

FLA stopped from selling photos

</B></FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE WIDTH="389" BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=6>
<TR>
<TD>
<FONT FACE="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="2">
<p> 
<FONT COLOR="gray" size=-2><B>contributed by flow</B>
</FONT>
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="BLACK">

Last month HNN reported that Florida was selling its drivers license
photos to a New Hampshire company to create a consumer anti-fraud
system.  After three attorneys filed suit a Judge terminated the
contract. The Nashua New Hampshire based company, Image Data LLC, has
already purchased DMV records from Colorado and South Carolina and
plans to continue marketing its product.

<p>
<a href="/archive.html?012699.html">HNN Archive for January 26,
1999</a><br>
<a
href="http://www.insidecentralflorida.com/news/1999/01/27/WFTV6_driverslicenses.html">Inside
Central Florida</a><br>
<p>
<FONT COLOR="Orange" size=-2><B>Late Update</B><br>
</FONT>
While Image Data LLC has already taken delivery of some photos the
overal sale of photos from Colorado has nixed.<br>
<a href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/0203id3.shtml">Rocky
Mountain News</a>
</FONT> 
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>
<!-- End Day -->
<!-- Begin Day --> 
<TABLE BGCOLOR="#555555" WIDTH="401" BORDER=0
CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=3>
